Cross-Validation for Correlated Data Paper Summary

 

 

Linear Mixed Model

(1)yi,j=ϕi,jtβ+bi+ϵi,j,i∈{1,…,I},j∈{1,…,ni}

where yi,j∈R is the jth observation for cluster i,ϕi,j∈Rp are the observed fixed effects covariates, β∈Rp is the fixed effects coefficients vector, bi∼N(0,σb2) are independent random effects and ϵi,j∼N(0,σϵ2) are the i.i.d. errors. Since all the observations in cluster i share the same random effect realization, they are correlated.

Cross-Validation

T , whole data set, is randomly partitioned into K folds, T1={yi,xi}i=1n1

T2={yi,xi}i=(n1+1)n2,…,TK={yi,xi}i=(nK−1+1)nK,1 where nk−nk−1 is the sample size in fold k and nK=n.

For each k∈{1,…,K}, the model is trained on the entire data except the kth  fold, denoted by T−k=⋃j≠kTj={y−k,X−k}. The prediction error of the trained model is then measured on the holdout fold, Tk={yk,Xk}, with respect to some loss function L(⋅,⋅) : R×R→R.

The CV prediction error estimator ,

(2)CV=1n∑k=1K∑i∈kthfoldL(yi,y^(xi;T−k))

where y^(xi;T−k) is the predictor of yi, constructed by training with T−K and predicting on xi.

Leave one out K=n.

Generalization Error

(3)generalization error=ETte,Ttr1nte∑i=1nteL(yte,i,y^(xte,i;Ttr))where
  • Ttr={ytr,Xtr}={ytr,i,xtr,i}i=1ntr −xtr,i is an i.i.d. sample from Px −ytr,i is sampled from Py∣x=xtr,i,s=s0
  • Tte={yte,Xte}={yte,i,xte,i}i=1nte −xte,i is an i.i.d. sample from Px −yte,i is sampled from Py∣x=xte,i,s=ste

Cross-validation is an estimator of generalization error.

General Formulation of CV Bias

(4)wcv=generalization error−cross-validation error(5)=ETte,Ttr(yte−y^(xte;Ttr))2−1nET‖y−y^cv(T)‖2,

where y^cv(T)=(y^(x1;T−1),…,y^(xn;T−n))t is the CV predictor of y. An unbiased estimator of the generalization error is:

(6)CVc=CV+wcv.

Criterion for CV Unbiasedness

Let PTte,Ttr and PTk,T−k be the joint distributions of {Tte,Ttr} and {Tk,T−k}, respectively. Theorem 2.1 describes a simple generic condition when no correction is required for CV.

Theorem 2.1. If PTte,Ttr=PTk,T−k∀k∈{1,..,n}, then wcv=0.

 

Unbiased LMM Case

Training set and test set have the same random effect realization i.e. ste=s0, i.e.,

(7)y=Φβ+Zs0+ϵytr=Φtrβ+Ztrs0+ϵtryte=ϕteβ+ztes0+ϵte

and

(8)X={Φ,Z},Φ∈Rn×(p−q),Z∈Rn×qXtr={Φtr,Ztr},Φtr∈R(n−1)×(p−q),Ztr∈R(n−1)×qxte={ϕte,zte},ϕte∈R1×(p−q),zte∈R1×q,

Biased LMM Case

When test set has new realization of random effect,

(9)y=Φβ+Zs0+ϵytr=Φtrβ+Ztrs0+ϵtryte=ϕteβ+zteste+ϵte

Definition of H

Definition 2.1. y^cv(T) is linear in y if:

(10)y^cv(T)=Hcvy

where Hcv∈Rn×n does not contain y and is constructed as follows:

(11)Hcv=[0h1,2…h1,nh2,10h2,n…hn,1hn,2…0]

hk,k′∈R∀k,k′∈{1,…,n}

 

Definition 2.2. Let hte∈R1×n−1 be the hat vector of yte, constructed from {Xtr,Cov⁡(yte,ytr)} in the same way as hk is constructed from {X−k,Cov⁡(yk,y−k)}.

 

Theorem 2.2. Let y^cv(T)=Hcvy be a linear predictor of y, and y^te(xte,Ttr)=hteytr is its corresponding predictor of yte. Then:

(12)wcv=2nE[tr⁡(HcvCov⁡(y,y))−nhteCov⁡(ytr,yte)].

Estimator of Generalization Error

Using Theorem 2.2, given Cov⁡(y,y) and Cov⁡(ytr ,yte ), an estimator of the generalization error for a linear predictor is:

(13)CV^c=1n(y−Hcvy)t(y−Hcvy)+2n[tr⁡(HcvCov⁡(y,y))−nhteCov⁡(ytr,yte)]

A special case is when Cov⁡(ytr,yte)=0. For example, in the clustered LMM setting that was given in Eq. (9), Cov⁡(ytr,yte)=0 when the latent variable realizations of ytr and yte, i.e., s0 and ste, are independent. In this case:

(14)CV^c=1n(y−Hcvy)t(y−Hcvy)+2ntr⁡[HcvCov⁡(y,y)]

Specifying hte and Cov⁡(ytr,y) in a hierarchical clustering

structure:

(15)yi,j,r=xi,j,rtβ+ui+bi,j+ϵi,j,r,ui∼N(0,σu2),bi,j∼N(0,σb2),ϵi,j,r∼N(0,σϵ2),∀i∈{1,…,I},j∈{1,…,J},r∈{1,…,R}.

Assume that the prediction goal is to estimate:

(16)yte=xtetβ+ute+bte+ϵte,

where ute∈[u1,…,uI], however bte does not depend on the realizations of {bi,j}i∈{1,…I},j∈{1,…,J}.

Prediction goal is relates to one of the high-level clusters but from a new low-level cluster.

  • Since hte is distributed as hk (for random k), then hte can be extracted by selecting a random hk from
  • Hcv.Cov⁡(ytr,yte) is extracted correspondingly as Cov⁡(y−k,yk∣b,ϵ), where b and ϵ are vectors containing {bi,j}i∈{1,…I},j∈{1,…,J} and {ϵi,j,r}i∈{1,…I},j∈{1,…,J},r∈{1,…,R}, respectively.
  • By conditioning on these vectors, the remaining covariance stems from u=[u1,…,uI] only, corresponding to the covariance between ytr and yte.
  • Simpler, nhteCov⁡(ytr,yte) can be replaced by tr⁡(HcvCov⁡(y,y∣b,ϵ)), such that:
(17)CV^c=1n(y−Hcvy)t(y−Hcvy)+2n[tr⁡(HcvCov⁡(y,y))−tr⁡(HcvCov⁡(y,y∣b,ϵ))]=1n(y−Hcvy)t(y−Hcvy)+2ntr⁡(HcvCov⁡(y,y∣u))

Simulation

The dependent variable, y∈Rn, was sampled from the following model:

(18)yi,j,k=0.1∑r=19xi,j,k,r+ui+∑r=12zi,j,k,rbi,j,r+ϵi,j,k,i∈{1,…,I},j∈{1,…,5},k∈{1,…,10},

where

Training Set:

  • the random effects:

    • Clusters: ui,
    • Subject: bi,j=[b1,b2] and ϵi,j,k are independent and distributed as follows:
    • Time: for each k
(19)ui∼indN(0,32),bi,j=[bi,j,1,bi,j,2]∈R2∼indN(0,[32001]),ϵi,j,k∼indN(0,1)

  • the covariates, {xr}r=19 are:

    • xi,j,k,1=1,xi,j,k,2=k,∀i,j,k are the intercept and the time covariates,
    • xi,j,k,r=ηi+δi,j,k,∀i,j,k and ∀r∈{3,…,9}, where ηi∼indN(0,1),δi,j,k∼ind N(0,1) are independent,

  • zi,j,k,1=1,zi,j,k,2=k ∀i,j,k are the covariates for random intercept and random slope.

Test Set with different cluster:

(20)yi,j,k te=0.1∑r=19xi,j,k,r te+ui te+∑r=12zi,j,k,rbi,j,r te+ϵi,j,k,i∈{1,…,I},j∈{1,…,5},k∈{1,…,10},

Generate the whole data set by using new realization of every random effect.

Test set with same cluster:

(21)yi,j,k te=0.1∑r=19xi,j,k,r te+ui +∑r=12zi,j,k,rbi,j,r te+ϵi,j,k,i∈{1,…,I},j∈{1,…,5},k∈{1,…,10},

Using the same cluster random effect realization ui.

 

Cross-validation error

Zcluster and Zsubject are defined as in the picture

Simulation Procedure

let n=I×J×K

1. Get the variance matrix

σcluster=1,σsubject1=1,σsubject2=3,σϵ=1

Vcluster=Zcluster(σclusterII×I)Zcluster⊤

Vwithout cluster=Zsubjectdiag[σsubject1,σsubject22…σsubject1,σsubject22]1×IJ⊤Zsubject⊤+σϵI

V=Vcluster+Vwithout cluster

2. Random effect Realization
  • Random Effect for training set

Random Clusters:

(22)u0=MVN(0×1n×1,Vcluster)

Random Effect without cluster for training set

(23)b0+ϵ0=MVN(0×1n×1,Vwithout cluster)

  • Random Effect for test set

    Random Clusters:

    (24)ute=MVN(0×1n×1,Vcluster)

    Random Effect without cluster for training set

    (25)bte+ϵte=MVN(0×1n×1,Vwithout cluster)
3. Generate Data
  • X1,•=1
  • X2,k=k
  • Xr,•∼N(0×1n×1,VX), where VX=Zcluster(II)Zcluster⊤+σδIn
  • Training set
(26)Y=Xβ+u0+b0+ϵ0

  • Test set with same clusters

    (27)Yte0=Xteβ+u0+bte+ϵte

  • Test set with different clusters

    (28)Yte=Xteβ+ute+bte+ϵte
4. Get the estimated variance matrix

Using LMER RMEL on training set to estimate σ^cluster,σ^subject1,σ^subject2,σ^ϵ

V^cluster=Zcluster⊤(σ^clusterII×I)Zcluster

V^without cluster=Zsubject⊤diag[σ^subject1,σ^subject22…σ^subject1,σ^subject22]1×IJ⊤Zsubject+σ^ϵI

V^=V^cluster+V^without cluster

GLS Formula
(29)Y^=(X⊤V−1X)−1X⊤V−1Y
5. Calculate the Hcv
(30)Hcv(i,−i)=(X−i⊤V(−i,−i)−1X−i)−1X−i⊤V(−i,−i)−1

where X−i is X without the i-th row, and V(−i,−i) is V without i-th row and i-th column. The i-th row i-th column of Hcv is zero, and Hcv(i,−i) is the i-th row without i-th column of Hcv.

And

(31)H^cv(i,−i)=(X−i⊤V^(−i,−i)−1X−i)−1X−i⊤V^(−i,−i)−1
6. Calculate Ycv and Y^cv.
(32)Ycv=HcvYY^cv=H^cvY

 

7. Cross-validation error
(33)CV=1n(Ycv−Y)2CV^=1n(Y^cv−Y)2
8. Correction

  • Correction and for new generated u and estimated correction

    (34)w=2ntr⁡(Hcv(VXr+V))w^=2ntr⁡(H^cvV^)

    where VXr is computed variance of covariates Xβ.

  • Correction and for same u and estimated correction

    (35)w=2n[tr⁡(Hcv(VXr+V))−tr⁡(Hcv(Vcluster)]w^=2n[tr⁡(H^cvV^)−tr⁡(H^cvV^cluster))]

 

9. Test Error
(36)Y^te=Xte(Xtr⊤Vtr−1Xtr)−1Xtr⊤Vtr−1Ytr

  • Test Error for new generated ute

    (37)Test Error=1n(Yte−Y^te)2

  • Test Error for u0

    (38)Test Error=1n(Yte0−Y^te)2
